# Story Wrap-Up Procedure

This is the standard wrap-up procedure. It runs automatically when any story-owner agent reaches `"complete"` phase (triggered by agent-autostart.md). It can also be invoked manually if the user says "wrap up", "close it out", or similar.

Do NOT re-discover MCP tool schemas; use the exact calls below.

Agent **IDs**: `frontend`, `backend`, `qa`, `ux`, `reviewer`, `devops`. Dashboard labels (Lasair, Brehon, Vigil, etc.) may differ — reset files by agent ID filenames (`.frontend-status.json`, etc.).

## 1. Find the story owner and PR

Scan ALL status files to find who owns the story and which agents participated:

```powershell
Get-ChildItem ".*-status.json" | ForEach-Object { Write-Host $_.Name; Get-Content $_ }
```

- The **story owner** is the agent whose file has a non-null `storyNumber` and a `prs[]` array (often `frontend`, `ux`, or `devops` in Mode A, or occasionally `reviewer` when owning implementation work).
- Also note which agents have `assignedPR` — support agents (`reviewer`, `devops` build gate) need resetting too
- Extract the `pullRequestId` from the owner's `prs[0].id` or a support agent's `assignedPR.id`

If no status file has an active story, fall back to the branch name: `feat/B-XXXXX-*` or `feature/<agent>/B-XXXXX-*` → `B-XXXXX`

## 2. Set PR to auto-complete

```
CallMcpTool: user-Azure DevOps / repo_update_pull_request
{
  "repositoryId": "Meitheal",
  "project": "Mosaic",
  "pullRequestId": <id>,
  "autoComplete": true,
  "mergeStrategy": "Squash",
  "deleteSourceBranch": true
}
```

## 3. Close the story in Agility

Try the local API first:
```powershell
$body = @{ number = "<storyNumber>"; status = "Released" } | ConvertTo-Json -Compress
Invoke-RestMethod -Uri "http://localhost:3847/api/agility/story-status" -Method Post -Body $body -ContentType "application/json" -TimeoutSec 5
```
If it fails (404, timeout), that's OK — the story auto-transitions when the PR merges.

Note: The Agility MCP `update_story_field` does NOT support a `status` field. Don't try it.

## 4. Reset ALL involved agents

Reset every agent that participated — not just the story owner.

### Story-owner agents (`frontend`, `ux`, `devops` Mode A, …)

These have `storyNumber`, `tasks[]`, `prs[]`. Reset to:
```json
{
  "storyNumber": null,
  "storyName": null,
  "currentPhase": "idle",
  "currentTask": null,
  "startedAt": null,
  "tokens": { "cloud": { "input": 0, "output": 0 }, "ollama": { "input": 0, "output": 0 } },
  "tasks": [],
  "prs": [],
  "cypress": { "lastRun": null, "total": 0, "passed": 0, "failed": 0, "skipped": 0, "failures": [] },
  "events": []
}
```

`ux` also has `collaborators` and `designSpec` — include those as `[]` and `null`.

### Support agents (`reviewer`, `devops` as build gate)

These have `assignedPR`. Reset to:

**Reviewer (`reviewer`):**
```json
{
  "assignedPR": null,
  "currentPhase": "idle",
  "requestedAt": null,
  "events": []
}
```

**DevOps build gate (`devops`):**
```json
{
  "currentPhase": "idle",
  "assignedPR": null,
  "events": []
}
```

### Clear all message files

```powershell
Get-ChildItem ".*-messages.json" | ForEach-Object { Set-Content $_ "[]" }
```

## 5. Confirm to user

Report:
- PR number, link, and merge strategy
- Story status (released or will auto-transition on merge)
- Which agents were reset (**by agent ID**, and mention dashboard display names only if helpful)
